column1: 64,438053,,,11/16/22(Wed)22:30:11,Anonymous,Should i drop out graphic design collegue?,"I started going in a meme university months ago and i thinks it&#039
column2: s utter shit, because we hardly ever do things related to the degree and lose so much time that i could use more efficiently if i could be self taught instead. Also, i plan on living from art (self taught) but was pressured by my mother to go an university and chose the graphic design degree, not only because it&#039
column3: s a discipline that im genuinely interested but also the thing that i could get the most of. I think that i could save so much money and time if i could drop out and learn all graphic design theory by myself, but i keep hearing that a degree is absolutely necessary to get jobs and be succesful, is that true?",th-3524945538,.jpg,474,592,200,250,1668655811050950,1668655811,pgJQzf13lnEgCZ9d6ZfePg==,43905,0,,should-i-drop-out-graphic-design-collegue,7,0,"[{'no': 438096, 'now': '11/18/22(Fri)01:28:31', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '<a href=""#p438069"" class=""quotelink"">&gt
column5:
438069
I never considered getting a marketing degree, mainly because graphic design is a more visual thing, which i think may suit me better for the kind of shit i want to make. Having said that, i will investigate more on the degrees you mentioned, thanks.

>
column8: One, learn how to spell college, you&#039
column9:
re in college.
Shit, my bad.
>
column10:
Two, graphic design is a huge field. Which part are you going to try and work in?
As i said, i entered because i wanted to learn about visual composition (colors, focus points, etc.) to integrate into a personal brand, so i can get more traction (if i memed myself or not is something maybe you could tell). Besides that, i wanted to make logos and posters.
>
column11:
Three, graphic design is one of the few fields where your portfolio and abilities can still get you hired without a degree
Nice to hear that, my mother always tells me that i wouldn'
column12: t get hired just because i won&#039
column13: t have a degree, which is kinda bullshit because one of our teachers even told us that everything that is and will be taught is already on th internet. Of course a degree will definetly help but i feel that it&#039
column14:
s more convenient to study on my own for some time.
>
column17: is a bit of bullshit. It&#039
column19:
s working practices and the tools, with some theory like color theory and such.
I am not really far into the career but a lot of times classes consist of learning some concept or doing something unrelated to the degree.', 'time': 1668752911, 'resto': 438053}, {'no': 438097, 'now': '11/18/22(Fri)01:32:03', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>
column22: You can teach yourself, but it&#039
column24: t learn on your own, or practices, like what the actual production pipeline you&#039
column25:
ll expected to be part of.
>
column26: it used to be you could get a night time part time gig and learn on the job for shit pay at an ad agency to learn the ropes, but those spots are highly coveted by tons of graduates from design schools who can&#039
column27:
t get a job.
How saturated is the market? And specially, would a client prefer someone with a good grasp on graphic design but WITHOUT a degree, or will they prefer someone that has a degree but isn'
column29:
So what makes you more hireable than them, especially since they can walk in, and get the job done with a minimum of questions and mistakes?
At the moment, nothing. That'
column30:
s why i plan to study on my own.
>
column31:
The number one thing we looked at was the portfolio, and if they could get the job done, and we could tell very quickly in the interview if they were clueless how to do that.
How do you know when they could get the job done? I have zero experience in jobs, so any kind of guidance will be great for the future.', 'time': 1668753123, 'resto': 438053}, {'no': 438128, 'now': '11/18/22(Fri)20:06:09', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>
column34:
How saturated is the market?
Very. GD degrees are very popular, and programs in colleges very full. There'
column35: s a lot of people on the street looking for a job with a mediocre design degree and portfolio, and it seems like that&#039
column36:
s been true since the rise of desktop publishing.
The key with any creative positions is your brain. You'
column37: re either good at technical details, like pre-press and production design, when you build up a layout to print properly and conform to styles and such, or you&#039
column38:
re good at ideas, pikcing colors, building the styles production designers follow, etc. That kind of job is typically not entry level.
>
column39:
How do you know when they could get the job done?
Asking them questions. Those jobs were in print production, so we could ask them about experience with things like CMYK, color correction, pre-flighting jobs for the press, how to set up bleeds and knock outs, things like that. There are a lot of nuts and bolts parts of print production they don'
column40: t teach in school, and it&#039
column41: s easy to see when someone is in over their head - but we&#039
column42: d also look for people who want to learn it. We&#039
column44: lot of prima donna designers who had the attitude of &quot
column49: This bitch is gonna cost us thousands in pre-press fees&quot
column51: re probably going to be looking at web based design, so it will be different issues.', 'time': 1668819969, 'resto': 438053}, {'no': 438172, 'now': '11/19/22(Sat)13:56:23', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '<a href=""#p438128"" class=""quotelink"">&gt
column55: s a lot of people on the street looking for a job with a mediocre design degree and portfolio, and it seems like that&#039
column56:
s been true since the rise of desktop publishing.
When i went to register they told me that many graduates instantly get a job when they finish the degree, but i still feel like this slow, expensive but safe way isn'
column58: Asking them questions. Those jobs were in print production, so we could ask them about experience with things like CMYK, color correction, pre-flighting jobs for the press, how to set up bleeds and knock outs, things like that. There are a lot of nuts and bolts parts of print production they don&#039
column59:
t teach in school
How does one get experience in things like that? what kind of material or things i should look for in jobs? I know very well that college doesn'

column10: re actually *trying* and making an effort. That&#039
column11: s the hardest part, anon. I&#039
column12:
m proud of you, son.

Now, your pic is pretty much lacking in all of the fundamental laws of design other than it'
column13:
s not a blank jpeg. You need to get familiar with the core fundamental attributes of art/design. The degree to which you attain understanding of these is the degree to which you will be able to create things that resonate with people and that are pleasing to the eye and brain.
If you'
column14: re a reader then get a book on graphic design fundamentals. If you&#039
column15: re not a reader (you should be, anon. The anon who reads lives a thousand lives), then search for &quot
column17:
on the Youtubes.

Some of the fundamental attributes of design are:
* Contrast
* Balance/Symmetry
* Proximity
* Visual hierarchy

Anything that is meant to convey information to another brain needs to be legible, and legibility should take priority over flashiness or '
column19: if you actually want to influence people or inform them through your work. In your case here, the color contrast of the text over the background is low and the font you used (and the fact that it&#039
column20: s all caps) makes it very hard to read. Along that line, but not as dire, is the fact that the I2P logo has a lot of similar color to the background so it kinda just melts into the background and isn&#039
column21:
t as legible.

And finally, young tadpole, a pro tip for future stuff: center-aligned text is almost always the wrong choice. Given any random amateur design, a poster let'
column22: s say, the one with left-aligned text is going to feel more legible and professional than one with centered shit. Again, that&#039
column23: s not gospel and there are times where you want centered shit. But 9/10 times it ain&#039
column24:
t it.

Uhhh final final thing: whitespace is your best fren. Go forth and kick ass, anon.', 'time': 1670025474, 'resto': 438625}, {'no': 438634, 'now': '12/03/22(Sat)00:10:54', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'Good first step would be changing the font to something immediately legible. I'

column5:

Because the basic typeface it resembles the Eurostile family (and its direct predecessor) and especially when it'
column6: s extended people have been conditioned to think &quot
column9: Eurostile is a popular font, particularly suitable for headings and signs. Its linear nature suggests modern architecture, with an appeal both technical and functional. The squarish shapes with their rounded corners evoke the appearance of television screens of the 1950s and 1960s. It is particularly popular in science fiction artwork and media set or produced in the 1960s and 70s, alongside other graphic design use. Eurostile and its antecedent Microgramma had a near-monopoly on science fiction typefaces through the end of the 20th century, before Ray Larabie, seeing an opening in the market, began designing more modern computer fonts for the genre and distributed them through freeware.&quot

column1: 86,438525,,,11/29/22(Tue)13:43:46,Anonymous,,Creating a holiday themed flyer. How would one go about recreating this kind of hand-stitched crochet look in PS? Texture packs? Or specific layer styles?,Screen Shot 2022-11-23 at 11.40.19 AM,.png,1788,1216,250,170,1669747426932943,1669747426,pr8OuBWWrEAp69KXxT2Lqw==,4297679,0,,creating-a-holiday-themed-flyer-how-would-one-go,1,0,"[{'no': 438529, 'now': '11/29/22(Tue)15:04:30', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '<a href=""#p438525"" class=""quotelink"">&gt
column3:
438525
first, thats not crochet, look up cross stitch and needlepoint fonts and youll findxall kinds of lettering and other elements.
That kind of work is based on a grid and is essentially pixellated so to start use a grid layer to establish the layout and size the type "
column5:
to fit with it, and if you import any other graphics do the same, and maybe adjust the color depth down so that the pixellated color areas match too.
For other types of needlework like embroidery a line pattern that mimics the stich directions can be overlaid, and similarly a screen/mesh pattern that matches the main grid size can be added over graphic elements to accentuate the look of being made up of blocks, and any areas that don'
column6: t follow that grid structure removed.', 'time': 1669752270, 'resto': 438525}]",1669752270,0.0,0.0,,

column1: 105,436160,,,09/29/22(Thu)14:33:55,Anonymous,Affinity Designer will become superior,"I&#039
column2: ve started using Adobe Illustrator for the last couple of days and holy shit, this program is made by autists. It&#039
column3: s unnecessarily complex and there are way too many things while using the pen tool that just don&#039
column4:
t make sense and make the work process that many times slower. And the layout is way too cluttered and feels crowded.
On the contrary, Affinity Designer allows a clean layout, a ridiculously easy to use pen tool and things like having a plethora of geometric shapes that make the work process a lot easier and quicker to get down.

The only things that I see Affinity Designer lacking are the mesh tool and the shape builder, may even add the width tool and having multiple gradients in one object as well. column12:
437916
yeah, funny.
I think it is very important to activate your conscious brain while designing. In reality this arguably presents itself by creating with a search for intent, Id say.
BUT.
If you fall for the trap of believing that every element of a design you do MUST ALWAYS be intentional, you are kinda blocking your more emotional/unconscious/musing (but random) side of your creative journey.
In the end you will find a balance of these that works for you and in your cases. and honestly looking at the different artists there are, you could end up on many places between the extremes and be successful with it.

nevertheless. one thing will stay the same.
the design (should be but) must not be so much done with intent, as it has to be suggesting intent to the viewer.

Its a fine line. A distinction, that we could probably spend some time debating on (and maybe even trash afterwards), but for now just consider that there are good designs of people who never really consciously reasoned why they are doing what they are doing, but who still manage to create pieces which make '
column14:
feel properly guided and taken care of.

take the iridescent sticker thing as an example.
it kinda looks like a random asset you slapped on there.
it doesnt really match the rest and you made it so tiny it looks as if you were uncertain even putting it on.
show intent and make it bigger!
